t destabilized accustomed ways of performing masculinity. At the same time, in their attempts to sustain their conceptions of masculinity these men maintained agency and developed coping strategies that prevented their full-scale emasculation. Huebel draws on a rich archive of diaries, letters, and autobiographies to interpret the experiences of these men, focusing on their roles as soldiers and protectors, professionals and breadwinners, and parents and husbands. Fighter, Worker, and Family Man sheds light on how the Nazis sought to emasculate Jewish men through propaganda, the law, and violence, and how in turn German-Jewish men were able to defy emasculation and adapt – at least temporarily – to their marginalized status as men.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGender identityzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish menzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1933-1945. 0aJewszGermanyxIdentityxHistoryy20th century. 0aMarginality, SocialzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMasculinityzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aHolocaust.  aJewish men.  aJews.  aNazi Germany.  aThird Reich.  aWWII.  aWorld War Two.  aconcentration camps.  agender and war.  agender history.  agender identity.  agender.  amasculinity.  amen.  amilitary masculinity.  asocial history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754125540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487541255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487541255/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPA